Just remember, your writing process is your own, it is not mine, it is not the other person's, and it is probably not a big name author. If it works for you, it works for you. That's all that matters.

And so like if we all collaborate together, it allows someone to find exactly what works for them. But if it's just me, it feels like my words will be taken as gospel/at face value and I really do not want that.

I do want to expand on this a bit and say that I do not mind giving writing advice if it's asked in a general chat. But one on one is just so uncomfortable. I really don't want to be looked at like someone's peer. I am learning just like you and the other people.

30. My best friend who is an accomplished writer. I can think of no one who I aspire to be like more. I use to have jealousy because she has books out (two in fact) and I'm just sitting alone in the VIP but now I know that she's amazing. 10/10 coolest person I know.

29. 'what the fuck why can't i read this ship? fine i'll write it myself fuck you all' or 'HEY. THIS? YEAH. FIC TIME.' it's mostly always been what I want to see but can't see because no one's done it or I'm fucking blind.
28. I like both! It's sometimes nice to just be done stuff but sometimes, it's good to have something ongoing. Both have their pros and cons, and I'm absolutely satisfied writing both.

27. I jump in a lot, but recently, I've been doing some light plotting with bullet points and even if I stray away from those, it helps. Because it allows me to figure out my start and my end. I'll share one at some point (my current ones are for secret fandom projects).
26. I use both Google Docs and Scrivener. Google Docs when I have stuff on the go, but Scrivener is my platform that I love so much. It's absolutely perfect. Highly recommend it.
25. Always music. If it's quiet, I will get to Think and that will lead to Bad Thoughts. Currently using this to write to; https://t.co/TwRJOzjGaO

24. Absolutely inspired. I see no reason for jealousy. I only have one piece of jealousy and it's that my rare pairs don't get as much love as my big ships, but overall, no jealousy to other writers. They're inspiring and I love 'em to bits.
23. Fanfiction. Oh, I want to write original work, but I don't think I'm mentally there yet. Someday. I'd like to try and finish an original book before I turn 40, so that's the dream.

22. I don't know about steadily, but I do feel like I'm improving. I'm sure there's times where I regress, but definitely feel more and more confident, which makes me think I'm improving. won't read my old work to check though you can't make me.

21. I try to challenge myself in a variety of ways when writing but also kind of try not to stray too far from what I'm comfortable writing. I try to have a mix. Maybe some more action in dialogue heavy stories for instance. That way, I'm not feeling too overwhelmed
20. Dialogue. I love writing dialogue. It feels so smooth for me to get through. I don't know if my dialogue SOUNDS good but I enjoy writing it the most.

19. Smut is the easy one, I'll say fight scenes too. I don't do a lot of action scenes because I am bad at it. I have recently learned that a fight scene should be like a conversation so I'm going with that.
18. Kind of everything. Pacing is probably my biggest one. I never know how fast or slow something should go and even reading I don't think I got a grasp on it.
(THAT SEEMED HARSH but there's been a few times where i have been pestered to do writing/critique for someone and i hated the entire thing. It's not my bag, and I'm sorry) 3/3

that by me giving advice, it feels like I'm controlling how people should/shouldn't write. I want people to explore their process. And I'll be with them through out the way and when we're done, we can talk. But if you just are like 'hey how should i-' do not. unless i know you.

17. No and do not ask me for writing advice/critique unless I know you very well. It's not that I am not willing to help, it's that I am just not comfortable with doing it. I don't want to give advice that doesn't work for people. Writing is such a personal thing (1/2)
16. Absolutely write more. There is no question about it. I write almost daily (and if not write, do something writing adjacent (Iike this)).

15. A one shot can be like 1 hour, but fics that are over 2000 are basically who the fuck knows. I will say, whole heartedly, that I can jam out like 4,000 words in a day and 8,000 over two days. But then I need a break.
14. I do (less now) roleplay, but for fic writing, it's incredibly personal for me to do. I cannot write fic with someone else. I really have to have that dividing line.
13. I share a lot. But I mostly write because I want to see it exist. If the fandom will not do it, I will.
12. I don't even know how to describe my process. It changes all the time. So you can ask, the answer just might not be satisfactory. Right now, I do light plotting through bullet points.

11. None on twitter. On Tiktok, it was all I followed but I had to leave Tiktok after The Incident (I spent 12 hours just scrolling through Tiktok and went this was too much). I follow mostly book reviewers here.
10. Like a 7/10 confidence. I'm not like this is the best shit ever but now a days I'm like hey. This is pretty good. Look at you go.
9. On average, probably an hour a day. If I were to really close shit down and work, that's usually what I can do. Sometimes I can do way more.
8. For fun right now but I do want to work on something to publish someday.

7. Books, yes. Sometimes I just need a boost of creativity there so I will read books to get a feel. But I don't really read fics for reference. In particular, I don't read them when writing something big because I don't want to get jumbled up.

6. I don't really have a least favorite genre? I don't like writing erotica that much anymore. I used to write a lot of smut and stuff but now it's no longer my vibe. It's also my least favorite thing in books to read lmao. I DNF'd a book just because of smut. Not a prude, swear
5. I write contemporary and fantasy most often. Those are just the ones I'm more comfortable sliding into because that's mainly what I read.
4. Yes, I do have an Ao3. I have two, but I keep them separate and I won't share them here. But I've posted about them in the past and on other accounts so you can find them there.

3. Yes! I did a writing program for like a Saturday back in like elementary/junior high school, and have done a variety of writing courses through college. I do plan to do some more because my library has free online courses.

2. I've been writing for pretty much as long as I've been able to write on the computer, roleplaying at age 11 i think? on Neopets. And just spiraling. I'd say my first actual fanfiction writing was like when I was 15. I wrote stories in school but like nothing I'd want to reread

1. Online. You cannot read my handwriting, no one can read my handwriting, no matter how hard I've tried. And oh my god do I try. It is a running joke at work where I will write down someone's info, and they have to confirm details again.
